<HEAD>ADVERTISEMENT.</HEAD>
<P>A Li&s;t of the encouragers names will be publi&s;hed in the third volume of this work; and all gentlemen that now chu&s;e to become &s;ub&s;cribers, may be &s;upplied with the fir&s;t volume at the moderate price of one Dollar. Sub&s;criptions are received by <HI>Robert Bell,</HI> Book&s;eller, and by all the Printers and Book&s;ellers in America. The &s;econd and third volumes will be for|warded as expeditiou&s;ly as po&s;&s;ible, and deli|vered to the &s;ub&s;cribers, in blue boards, at the price of one Dollar each.</P>
<P>Memorandum. <HI>THIS Volume can only be &s;old to tho&s;e GENTLEMEN who are now willing to Sub&s;cribe for the Second and Third Volumes of this celebrated Hi&s;tory, by giving in their Names as Encouragers.</HI></P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="title page">
<PB REF="011837_0002_0F9D86F0F2E32538" MS="y">
<P>THE HISTORY OF THE REIGN OF CHARLES THE FIFTH, EMPEROR OF GERMANY; And of all the KINGDOMS and STATES in EUROPE, during his Age.</P>
<P>TO WHICH IS PREFIXED, A VIEW OF THE PROGRESS OF SOCIETY IN EUROPE, From the Subver&s;ion of the ROMAN EMPIRE, to the Beginning of the Sixteenth Century.</P>
<P>CONFIRMED BY Hi&s;torical PROOFS and ILLUSTRATIONS.</P>
<P>IN THREE VOLUMES.</P>
<P>By WILLIAM ROBERTSON, D. D. PRINCIPAL of the UNIVERSITY of EDINBURGH, and HISTORIOGRAPHER to His MAJESTY for SCOTLAND: <HI>Author of the late elegant Hi&s;tory of Scotland.</HI></P>
<P>VOLUME THE FIRST.</P>
<P><HI>AMERICA:</HI> PRINTED FOR THE SUBSCRIBERS.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="dedication">
<PB REF="011837_0003_0F9D86F1C4D37D28">
<HEAD>TO THE KING.</HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>I PRESUME to lay before Your Ma|je&s;ty the Hi&s;tory of a Period, which, if the abilities of the Writer were equal to the dignity of the Subject, would not be unworthy the attention of a Monarch, who is no le&s;s a Judge than a Patron of Literary Merit.</P>
<P>HISTORY claims it as her prerogative to offer in&s;truction to KINGS, as well as to their people. What reflections the Reign of the Emperor CHARLES V. may &s;ugge&s;t to your Maje&s;ty, it becomes not me to conjecture. But your Subjects cannot ob|&s;erve the various calamities, which that Monarch's ambition to be di&s;tingui&s;hed as a Conqueror, brought upon his dominions, without recollecting the felicity of their own times, and looking up with gratitude to their Sovereign, who, during the fer|vour of youth, and amid&s;t the career of victory, po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed &s;uch &s;elf-command, and maturity of judgment, as to &s;et bounds
<PB REF="011837_0004_0F9D86F272E91C90">
to his own triumphs, and prefer the ble&s;|&s;ings of peace to the &s;plendour of military glory.</P>
<P>POSTERITY will not only celebrate the Wi&s;dom of Your Maje&s;ty's choice, but will enumerate the many Virtues, which render Your Reign con&s;picuous for a &s;a|cred regard to all the duties, incumbent on the Sovereign of a Free People.</P>
<P>IT is our happine&s;s to feel the influence of the&s;e Virtues; and to live under the dominion of a Prince, who delights more in promoting the Publick Welfare, than in receiving the ju&s;t Prai&s;e of his royal beneficence. I am,</P>
<CLOSER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE>
<SIGNED>YOUR MAJESTY's Mo&s;t faithful Subject, And mo&s;t dutiful Servant, WILLIAM ROBERTSON.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="dedication">
<PB REF="011837_0005_0F9D86F332469EE8">
<P>THIS AMERICAN EDITION, OF THE CELEBRATED HISTORY OF CHARLES THE FIFTH, Is mo&s;t re&s;pectfully and gratefully ADDRESSED TO JOHN DICKINSON, E&s;quire; And to all GENTLEMEN SUBSCRIBERS, Whether of the BAR&mdash;The PULPIT. The Faculty&mdash;The Mercantile&mdash; Or manufacturing PROFESSIONS,
<PB REF="011837_0006_0F9D86F3F48FBFE0">
who voluntarily, and without any other application than public adverti&s;ements, contributed their names as encourag|ers of American manufactures, thus prac|tically demon&s;trating true patrioti&s;m, a real affection for the welfare of their country, which inciteth not only to meer words, but al&s;o to noble actions, that vivifieth individuals, and tendeth towards the elevation and enriching of THE LAND WE LIVE IN.</P>
<CLOSER><SALUTE>GENTLEMEN,</SALUTE>
<SIGNED>I remain, Your much obliged, Humble Servant, The EDITOR.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="table of contents">
<PB REF="011837_0007_0F9D86F4B6336590">
<HEAD>CONTENTS OF VOLUME THE FIRST.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="contents of first text">
<DIV3 TYPE="contents of section">
<HEAD>View of the progre&s;s of Society in Europe, with re|&s;pect to interior Government, Laws and Manners. <HI>SECTION FIRST.</HI></HEAD>
<P>The effects of the Roman power on the &s;tate of Europe&mdash; The de&s;olation which it occa&s;ioned&mdash;The improvements which it introduced&mdash;The bad con&s;equences of their dominion&mdash;The irruption of the barbarous nations&mdash;State of the countries from which they i&s;&s;ued&mdash;The people fit for daring enter|prizes&mdash;The motives of their fir&s;t excur&s;ions&mdash;Their rea&s;ons for &s;ettling in the countries which they conquered&mdash;The ex|tent of their &s;ettlements&mdash;The circum&s;tances which occa&s;ion|ed the downfal of the Roman Empire&mdash;The circum&s;tances which contributed to the &s;ucce&s;s of the barbarous nations&mdash; The &s;pirit with which they carried on war&mdash;The de&s;olation which they brought upon Europe&mdash;The univer&s;al change which they occa&s;ioned in the &s;tate of Europe&mdash;From this &s;tate of di&s;order the laws of government, now e&s;tabli&s;hed, mu&s;t be traced&mdash;The principles on which the Northern nations made their &s;ettlements in Europe&mdash;The feudal government
<PB REF="011837_0008_0F9D86F571AB9F38">
gradually e&s;tabli&s;hed among them&mdash;National defence the great object of fedual policy&mdash;The feudal government defec|tive in its provi&s;ions for interior order in &s;ociety&mdash;It pre|vented nations likewi&s;e from acting with vigour in their ex|ternal operations.&mdash;The fatal effects of this &s;tate of &s;ociety on &s;ciences and arts&mdash;Upon religion&mdash;Upon the character and virtues of the human mind&mdash;From the beginning of the eleventh century government and manners begin to improve&mdash; Nece&s;&s;ary to point out the cau&s;es and events which contri|bute towards this improvement&mdash;The tendency of the Cru|&s;ades to introduce a change in government and manners&mdash; The more remote cau&s;es of the&s;e expeditions&mdash;The immediate occa&s;ion of them&mdash;The &s;ucce&s;s of the Cru&s;ades&mdash;The benefici|al effects of the Cru&s;ades on manners&mdash;Their influence on the &s;tate of property&mdash;Their commercial effects&mdash;The e&s;ta|bli&s;hment of communities favourable to government and or|der&mdash;The ancient &s;tate of cities&mdash;The freedom of cities fir&s;t e&s;tabli&s;hed in Italy&mdash;Is introduced into France and into other countries of Europe&mdash;Its happy effects upon the condition of the inhabitants&mdash;Upon the power of the nobility&mdash;Upon the power of the crown&mdash;Upon the increa&s;e of indu&s;try&mdash;The inhabitants of cities acquire political power as members of the con&s;titution&mdash;The happy effects of this upon govern|ment&mdash;The people acquire liberty by enfranchi&s;ement&mdash;The motives and progre&s;s of this&mdash;The effects of this upon the improvement of &s;ociety&mdash;The introduction of a more regular admini&s;tration of ju&s;tice, contributes to the improvement of &s;ociety&mdash;This effected by aboli&s;hing the practice of private war&mdash;Original ideas of men concerning ju&s;tice&mdash;The&s;e lead to the practice of private war&mdash;The pernicious effects of
<PB REF="011837_0009_0F9D86F6308AB260">
it&mdash;Various methods in order to aboli&s;h it&mdash;The prohibition of trial by judicial combat, another improvement in the ad|mini&s;tration of ju&s;tice&mdash;Defects in the judicial proceedings of the middle ages&mdash;The&s;e introduced the practice of appeal|ing to heaven&mdash;Particularly by judicial combat&mdash; The introduction of this practice favoured by the &s;uper&s;tition of the middle ages&mdash;and likewi&s;e by their martial &s;pirit&mdash; It becomes univer&s;al&mdash;The pernicious effects of it&mdash;Various expedients for aboli&s;hing this practice.&mdash;The privilege of appealing from the courts of the barons, another great im|provement in the admini&s;tration of ju&s;tice&mdash;Origin of the &s;upreme and independent juri&s;diction of the nobility&mdash;The ex|tent and bad effects of this privilege&mdash;Expedients employed in order to limit or aboli&s;h it&mdash;The regulations of the canon law promote a more perfect admini&s;tration&mdash;The progre&s;s of eccle&s;ia&s;tical u&s;urpation&mdash;The plan of eccle&s;ia&s;tical ju|ri&s;prudence more perfect than that in the civil courts&mdash;The good effects of imitating and adopting it&mdash;The revival of the Roman law contributes more liberal ideas concerning ju&s;tice and order&mdash;The circum&s;tances from which the Roman law fell into oblivion&mdash;Circum&s;tances which favoured the reviv|al of it&mdash;The effects of this upon the ideas of men, and the di&s;pen&s;ation of ju&s;tice&mdash;From all the&s;e aro&s;e a di&s;|tinction in profe&s;&s;ions&mdash;The effects of this on Society&mdash; The &s;pirit of chivalry introduces more liberal &s;enti|ments, and more generous manners&mdash;Origin of chival|ry&mdash;Its beneficial effects&mdash;The progre&s;s of &s;cience has great influence on the manners and characters of men&mdash;Ignorance of the middle ages&mdash;The fir&s;t literary efforts ill directed and the cau&s;es of this&mdash;They had however con&s;iderable effects&mdash; A circum&s;tance which prevented their being more exten|&s;ive
<PB REF="011837_0010_0F9D86F86B415D40">
&mdash;Its influence on manners merits attention&mdash;The pro|gre&s;s of commerce had great influence on manners and go|vernment&mdash;Low &s;tate of commerce in the middle ages&mdash; Cau&s;es of its revival&mdash;Fir&s;t among the Italians&mdash;Then by means of the Han&s;eatick league&mdash;Commerce makes progre&s;s in the Netherlands&mdash;And in England&mdash;The beneficial ef|fects of this.</P>
<P><HI>From page 1, to page 65.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="contents of section">
<HEAD>View of the Progre&s;s of Society in Europe, with re|&s;pect to the command of the national force requi|&s;ite in foreign operations.&mdash;<HI>SECTION SECOND.</HI></HEAD>
<P>STATE of &s;ociety greatly improved at the beginning of the fifteenth century&mdash;Still defective with re&s;pect to the command of the national force&mdash;The power of Monarchs ve|ry limited&mdash;Their revenues &s;mall&mdash;Their armies unfit for conque&s;t&mdash;They are incapable of forming any general or ex|ten&s;ive plan of operation&mdash;They were little connected with each other&mdash;A confirmation of this from the affairs of France&mdash;From tho&s;e of Spain&mdash;From tho&s;e of Germany&mdash; This inactivity occa&s;ioned entirely by the &s;tate of govern|ment&mdash;Events happened during the fifteenth century which rendered the efforts of nations more powerful and exten|&s;ive&mdash;The fir&s;t of the&s;e was the depriving the Engli&s;h of their territories on the continent&mdash;The effect of this on in|crea&s;ing the power of the French monarchy&mdash;On the &s;tate of the military force in the nation&mdash;It occa&s;ions the introduc|tion of &s;tanding armies&mdash;The effects of this&mdash;The monarchs of France encouraged to extend their prerogative&mdash;The pro|gre&s;s of the royal power under Charles <HI>VII.</HI>&mdash;Under Louis
<PB REF="011837_0011_0F9D86F886EF3138">
<HI>XI.</HI>&mdash;His mea&s;ures for humbling the nobility&mdash;And of di|viding them&mdash;He adds to the number of &s;tanding forces&mdash; He augments the revenues of the crown&mdash;His addre&s;s in managing the a&s;&s;embly of &s;tates&mdash;He enlarges the bounds of the French monarchy&mdash;By all the&s;e the French government rendered more active and enterprizing&mdash;Steps taken towards extending the power of the crown in England&mdash;And in Spain&mdash;Events happened, which called the &s;everal mo|narchs to exert the new powers which they had acquired&mdash; The fir&s;t of the&s;e events was the marriage of the heire&s;s of the hou&s;e of Burgundy&mdash;The importance of this to the &s;tate of Europe&mdash;Views of Louis <HI>XI.</HI> with re&s;pect to it&mdash;The &s;in|gular cour&s;e which he followed&mdash;The marriage of Maxi|milian with the heire&s;s of Burgundy&mdash;The influence of that upon the &s;tate of Europe&mdash;The next con&s;iderable event was the inva&s;ion of Italy, by Charles <HI>VIII.</HI>&mdash;The motives of this&mdash;His re&s;ources for this enterprize&mdash;His preparations for it&mdash;Its &s;ucce&s;s&mdash;Its effects, particularly in giving ri&s;e to the &s;y&s;tem concerning a balance of power&mdash;This becomes the great object of policy, fir&s;t in Italy, and then over all Europe&mdash;The wars in Italy render &s;tanding armies gene|ral&mdash;Teach the Europeans the &s;uperior importance of in|fantry in war&mdash;National infantry e&s;tabli&s;hed in Germany&mdash; In Spain&mdash;The Italian wars occa&s;ion an increa&s;e of the public revenues in Europe&mdash;The league of Cambray, another important occurrence&mdash;The motives of it&mdash;The rapid pro|gre&s;s of the Confederates&mdash;Divi&s;ion ari&s;es among them&mdash; New objects of their policy and ambition&mdash;By this the inter|cour&s;e among the European nations increa&s;es.&mdash;They are prepared for the tran&s;actions of the &s;ixteenth century.</P>
<P><HI>From page 65, to page 97.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="contents of section">
<PB REF="011837_0012_0F9D86F9303EC0F8">
<HEAD>View of the political Con&s;titution of the principal States of Europe, at the Commencement of the &s;ixteenth Century. <HI>SECTION THIRD.</HI></HEAD>
<P>A Con&s;iderable variety in the con&s;titution of the different nations of Europe,&mdash;Nece&s;&s;ary to explain the &s;tate of each when Charles <HI>V.</HI> began his reign&mdash;The &s;tate of Italy&mdash; The papal dignity the highe&s;t in Europe&mdash;Origin and pro|gre&s;s of the Papal power&mdash;The territories of the Popes in|adequate to &s;upport their &s;piritual juri&s;diction&mdash;Their au|thority in their own territories extremely limited&mdash;It was circum&s;cribed by the ambition of the Roman barons&mdash;And by the turbulence of the Roman people&mdash;Alexander <HI>VI.</HI> and Julius <HI>II.</HI> render the Popes con&s;iderable princes&mdash;Defects in the nature of eccle&s;ia&s;tical dominion&mdash;The Popes derive &s;ome advantages from the union of their &s;piritual and tem|poral authority&mdash;Con&s;titution of the republic of Venice with its ri&s;e and progre&s;s&mdash;De&s;ects in its government, particu|larly with re&s;pect to its military operations&mdash;Excellence of its naval in&s;titutions&mdash;The extent of its commerce&mdash;The con|&s;titution of Florence&mdash;The con&s;titution of the kingdom of Na|ples&mdash;State of the di&s;pute concerning the right of &s;ucce&s;&s;ion to the crown&mdash;Preten&s;ions of the French and Spani&s;h mo|narchs&mdash;State of the dutchy of Milan, and the right of &s;uc|ce&s;&s;ion to it&mdash;Ri&s;e and progre&s;s of the di&s;putes concerning this&mdash;The con&s;titution and government of Spain&mdash;Conquered by the Vandals&mdash;The Chri&s;tians gradually recover dominion
<PB REF="011837_0013_0F9D86FA002546F8">
in Spain&mdash;The union of its various kingdoms&mdash;Their ancient cu&s;|toms and laws re&s;erved amid&s;t all their revolutions&mdash;Which renders their &s;tate in &s;ome degree &s;imilar to that of other nati|ons of Europe&mdash;Certain peculiarities in their con&s;titution and laws&mdash;The prerogative more limited, and the immunities of the people more exten&s;ive&mdash;In&s;tances of this&mdash;The con&s;tituti|on and government of Aragon&mdash;Office and juri&s;diction of the Ju&s;tiza&mdash;The regal power circum&s;cribed within very narrow limits&mdash;Con&s;titutionand government of Ca&s;tile&mdash;Va|rious cau&s;es of the limited authority of the Spani&s;h Mo|narchs&mdash;Mea&s;ures of different Princes in order to extend their power, particularly of Ferdinand and I&s;abella&mdash; Ferdinand's different &s;chemes for abridging the privile|ges and power of the nobility&mdash;Particularly by annexing the grand ma&s;ter&s;hips of three orders to the crown.&mdash;And by circum&s;cribing the juri&s;diction of the nobility&mdash;Notwith&s;tanding all the&s;e, the government of Spain &s;till extremely free&mdash;Con&s;titution and government of France&mdash;Power of the general a&s;&s;emblies under the fir&s;t race of Kings&mdash;Under the &s;econd&mdash;Under the third&mdash;The power of the general a&s;&s;embly le&s;s con&s;iderable and le&s;s exten&s;ive&mdash; The crown begins to acquire legi&s;lative authority&mdash;And the power of levying taxes&mdash;Government of France becomes purely monarchical&mdash;The exerci&s;e of prerogative restrained by the privileges of the nobility&mdash;And by the juri&s;diction of the parliaments, particularly that of Paris&mdash;Con&s;titution and government of the German empire&mdash;Its &s;tate under Charle|magne and his de&s;cendants&mdash;Other families are rai&s;ed to the imperial dignity&mdash;The German nobility acquire independant and &s;overeign authority&mdash;The German eccle&s;ia&s;ticks rai&s;ed to
<PB REF="011837_0014_0F9D86FAB0EE3AD8">
the &s;ame power&mdash;The fatal effects of aggrandizing the cler|gy&mdash;The conte&s;ts between the Popes and Emperors, and the con&s;equences of the&s;e&mdash;The imperial authority gradual|ly declines&mdash;A total change in the political con&s;titution of the Empire&mdash;Expedients for putting an end to this &s;tate of anarchy&mdash;Particularly by the in&s;titution of the imperi|al chamber&mdash;At the beginning of the &s;ixteenth century, the Empire an a&s;&s;ociation of &s;overeign &s;tates&mdash;Peculiari|ties in the nature of this a&s;&s;ociation&mdash;The defects in the con&s;titution of the Empire&mdash;Ari&s;ing from the limited pow|er of the Emperors&mdash;From the nature of their title and preten&s;ions&mdash;From the manner in which they were elect|ed&mdash;From the different forms of government e&s;tabli&s;hed in the &s;tates which compo&s;ed the Germanick body&mdash;From the oppo&s;ition between the &s;eculiar and eccle&s;ia&s;tical members&mdash; From the unequal di&s;tribution of wealth and power among the members&mdash;All the&s;e render the Germanick body inca|pable of acting with union and vigour&mdash;View of the Turki&s;h government&mdash;Its origin&mdash;Its de&s;potic geni|us&mdash;Power of the Sultan limited by religion&mdash;And by the military&mdash;Origin of the Janizaries&mdash;Their va&s;t influence in the Turki&s;h government&mdash;Progre&s;s of the Turks towards dominion&mdash;Advantages which they po&s;&s;e&s;|&s;ed over the Chri&s;tian powers in the &s;ixteenth century.&mdash;</P>
<P><HI>From page 97, to page 154.</HI></P>
</DIV3>
