<DIV2 TYPE="contents of second text">
<HEAD>The HISTORY of the Reign of CHARLES the Fifth.&mdash; BOOK FIRST, PART FIRST.</HEAD>
<P>THE birth of <HI>Charles V.</HI>&mdash;His dominions, and the events by which he acquired them&mdash;Philip and Jo|anna, his father and mother vi&s;it Spain&mdash;Ferdinand jea|lous of Philip's power&mdash;I&s;abella's &s;olicitude with re&s;pect to him and her daughter&mdash;Di&s;order of Joanna's mind&mdash; Birth of Ferdinand, afterwards Emperor&mdash;Death of I&s;abella&mdash;Her will appointing Ferdinand regent of Ca&s;|tile&mdash;Ferdinand acknowledged as regent by the Cortes, The Ca&s;tilians di&s;&s;atisfied&mdash;Philip endeavours to obtain the government of Ca&s;tile&mdash;He requires Ferdinand to re|&s;ign the regency&mdash;Ferdinand abandoned by the Ca&s;tilian nobles&mdash;Ferdinand re&s;olves to marry, in order to exclude his daughter from the throne&mdash;Marries a niece of the French King&mdash;A treaty between Ferdinand and Philip.&mdash; Philip and Joanna &s;et &s;ail for Spain&mdash;The nobility of Ca&s;tile declare for Philip&mdash;Ferdinand re&s;igns the regency of Ca&s;tile and retires to Aragon&mdash;Philip and Joanna acknowledged as King and Queen by the Cortes&mdash;Death
<PB REF="011837_0016_0F9D86FCF57C46A8">
of Philip&mdash;The di&s;order of Joanna's mind increa&s;es&mdash; She is incapable of government&mdash;Maximilian and Ferdi|nand competitors for the regency&mdash;The Emperor, Ferdinand, ab&s;ent, on a vi&s;it to his kingdom of Naples.&mdash;Acquires the regency of Ca&s;tile, chiefly through the influence of cardi|nal Ximenes&mdash;Ferdinand returns to Spain&mdash;His pru|dent admini&s;tration&mdash;Conque&s;t of Oran&mdash;Acqui&s;ition of Navarre&mdash;Ferdinand jealous of his grand&s;on Charles. Endeavours to exclude him from the Spani&s;h kingdoms, by a will in favour of young Ferdinand&mdash;Is per&s;uaded to alter that will and dies&mdash;Education of Charles <HI>V.</HI>&mdash;The fir&s;t openings of his character&mdash;The &s;tate of Spain requires a vigorous admini&s;tration&mdash;Ferdinand had appointed car|dinal Ximenes regent&mdash;Cardinal Adrian appointed regent by Charles&mdash;Ximenes obtains the &s;ole direction of affairs. His precautions again&s;t the infant Don Ferdinand&mdash; Charles a&s;&s;umes the title of King&mdash;Recognized as &s;uch through the influence of Ximenes&mdash;His &s;chemes for extend|ing the prerogative&mdash;By depre&s;&s;ing the nobility&mdash;By forming a body of troops depending on the crown&mdash;By recalling the grants of former monarchs to the nobility&mdash; The nobles oppo&s;e his mea&s;ures&mdash;But without &s;ucce&s;s&mdash; Thwarted by Charles's Flemi&s;h mini&s;ters&mdash;An additional number of regents appointed&mdash;Ximenes retains the direc|tion of affairs.</P>
